The Prague Stock Exchange crashes into the minus at the close of business.
After the steep fall in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange was able to correct the losses.
Transactions with ČEZ shares reached almost half of the normal day-to-day business.
At the beginning of Tuesday's business, the Prague Stock Exchange followed Monday's slump by a further six percentage points.
This time the reason for the break-in was on Wall Street.
In the Czech Republic, too, the market’s response to the outcome of the vote of the American House of Representatives, which had refused to support a stabilisation plan for the financial sector there, is evident.
Case of shares in Asia
On Tuesday, stocks on the stock exchanges in Asia experienced a dramatic event, although the indices were able to offset some of the losses during the day.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng Stock Exchange index lost almost four percentage points in the course of the business day, but was later able to offset some of the losses, resulting in a decrease of about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which observes the movement of Chinese shares on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, and the markets in Shanghai were closed.
The shares on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but then reduced the losses to 4.3 percent.
The stock exchange in Taiwan fell by 3.6 percent according to the index there.
"The timing of the bailout in the US is uncertain and will influence the financial markets worldwide," said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority.
Hong Kong, although part of China, determines its monetary policy itself, i.e. independently of the Chinese Central Bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as those in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, American legislators should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible and adopt the draft financial support.
Otherwise, it would threaten that other countries would also be affected by the break-in.
A Bloodbath of American Stocks
On Monday, the U.S. House of Representatives rejected the plan to support the financial system, for which up to 700 billion dollars (almost 12 trillion Kč) should be spent.
Legislators thus ignored President George Bush's request to support the plan.
Bush believes that the plan would address the underlying causes of the financial crisis and thus help stabilise the entire economy.
The American stocks were in a bloodbath on Monday, and the main stock indices recorded the biggest slump in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell by almost seven percent, and a similar slump was most recently recorded in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but there were hardly any signs that the draft would not get through in the House of Representatives, the index experienced a free fall.
Congress makes concession: US government may pump 700 billion dollars into banks
The top representatives of U.S. Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of financial assistance agreement for the U.S. financial system.
This will be voted on at the beginning of next week.
American legislators made a breakthrough in discussions on the adoption of a bailout plan in the form of financial assistance to the American financial system to the tune of $700 billion (about 12 trillion kroner).
However, this does not mean victory.
In fact, Congressmen still have to negotiate some details of the agreement before they can publish and vote on the final version of the law.
The plan to support the financial system will be negotiated at the American Congress on Monday.
On Sunday, the Chairman of the Banking and Financial Services Committee, Barney Frank, told Reuters.
According to different data, the Senate could probably vote on the plan at the earliest on Wednesday.
According to economists, a communication on the adoption of the plan should be the first major psychological factor in stimulating financial markets.
After that, however, there would be a "disillusionment" due to the complicated mechanisms, as one could also help the markets in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our different views on what a market stabilization package should look like," said the Democrat Nancy Pelosi to the agency Bloomberg.
According to her, a final vote could still take place on Sunday.
Representatives of the legislators met with U.S. Secretary of State Henry Paulson on Sunday night to give the government fund its final form.
This provides for the purchase of unsaleable mortgage assets from financial companies, which plunge the financial firms into heavy losses and endanger the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
The recovery plan needs to be continued further, but I think we are at our goal," says Paulson.
A signal for Asian business
The global financial crisis is also clearly reflected in the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to the Democratic senator of Nevada, Harry Reid, legislators are trying to reach a final agreement before Sunday in Congress.
This is to reassure investors of Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone, where a decision by the Congress could influence business on Monday.
So far, however, it has not been quite clear when both US Congressional Chambers will vote on the law, nor is there any clarity as to whether the negotiations could still fail at the last minute due to a problem.
Legislators hope that it will be adopted in the next few days.
But the law will undergo some changes.
The total amount earmarked for assistance to the system will be divided into two parts.
The initial 350 billion dollars will be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush demanded.
But Congress can block the distribution of the rest of the money if it has the impression that the program does not fulfil its function, at a further $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush values progress in negotiations positively
Although the president has a right of veto in this decision, Congress can overrule its veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program has remained, based on obtaining finance for the purchase of bad mortgage securities whose value has fallen, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are no longer able to repay their mortgages.
"We worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the law on Sunday, the Senate then on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
American President Bush was also pleased with the progress made.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said Bush was satisfied with Saturday's progress and "estimated the two-sided effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of golden parachutes
The chairman of the banking committee of the Senate, Christopher Dodd, the chief negotiator, said that the legislators had agreed on responsibility for the money program, the protection of taxpayers against losses, the conclusion of benefits and a timetable for financing the plan.
The new law also aims to limit the so-called golden parachutes for directors of companies participating in the programme and sets up a committee to oversee the fund.
This is to be headed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard to achieve this and we have made great progress towards an agreement that works and is important for the market and for all Americans," says Paulson.
The plan also expects help for homeowners who have problems with the repayment of their mortgage.
The government should negotiate new mortgage rates that it buys, with the aim of reducing the monthly costs for debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological assistance
According to Patria Finance's chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but implementation will be very difficult.
"This is because one does not know by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets are bought up.
This will be crucial for how the financial sector and the government share the losses among each other," Marek told the iHNed.cz server this week.
According to Marek, whether the plan is being adopted now or at the beginning of next week is not decisive.
"It is much more important for Congressmen to agree to support the plan and to say goodbye to it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement on adoption is the most important thing at this moment," Marek stressed.
