The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and the Czech suppliers offer practically all the services offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe he won't be waiting for long.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that Czech mobile operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the ČTÚ telecommunications authority, which pointed out that the price of an SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the European Commission's final steps in regulating roaming charges, it is likely that there will be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really makes a battle announcement.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, because in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain that there is an extremely high level of competition on the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák often agrees with this, who in the past had often said that there was no place for another supplier in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has much chance (by the way, it would probably hardly find frequencies).
But there is one more possibility - a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual providers into the mobile phone market brought with it a significant price reduction, to which then also the classical mobile phone providers had to react.
Even before such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, there were similar voices to those in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, it doesn't take long to look for examples.
In February we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to attract more than 100 thousand customers, making it the fifth largest provider in the country.
Behind Mobilking stands the financial group Penta, which owns among other things U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual providers is that one can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to be able to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually stand out as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a rather good move to focus on a non-clichee target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and who they can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could also gain a foothold in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone Miroslav Čepický's press spokesman also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
It is also relatively saturated from the point of view of service provision."
In the Czech Republic, mobile operators feel that there is no chance
But it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very hopeful.
Mobilking will be more likely to enter the market in other countries in our region," says Jana Studničková, press officer of the Penta financial group, in a telephone call for Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
Their interest in launching a virtual mobile provider has been demonstrated for a long time by the GTS Novera group, which wants to take a further step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the area of corporate clients.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed network services, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them, we have already been able to achieve progress in negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl, press officer.
Maybe better times are coming now.
Unofficial information suggests that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has large specificities compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area", says in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefónica O2.
Other suppliers also point to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile Press Spokeswoman Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with O2's statement: "So far, we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which to build on."
And she adds: "By the end of the year, hardly any virtual provider will appear on the T-Mobile network.
At this moment, we should already have a concrete offer in order to be able to think in the short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention more on fulfilling the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický comments: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of sharing costs and infrastructure.
This is exactly what we see as the best from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - hand in hand with the suppliers
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider means more competition, this would lead to falling prices and thus also to a decline in profits.
Why, then, should such a competitor be made easier to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull together when it comes to something also proves the long back and forth about the emergence of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards ČTÚ came at the time when U:fon came onto the market, from the company T-Mobile.
This is also demonstrated by the publicly available information from the ČTÚ websites.
Now, however, U:fon is the right argument for why a virtual provider should not be allowed.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has also recently been strengthened by the entry of a fourth mobile provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, on its services."
However, given this approach by mobile operators, the absolute lack of interest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not only the attitude of the Czech Republic, which unfortunately - unlike Great Britain and other highly developed countries - does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition.
It has only the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, took its very typical attitude to this whole problem.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile provider and a virtual provider via the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classical suppliers", said Kristián Chalupa from the External Relations Department of the ÚOHS in his answer to our request.
Such a formulation would not surprise suppliers’ representatives.
This is more than a concern of an authority representing consumer interests and, among other things, ensuring that no one abuses their position on the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In foreign countries, where virtual providers work quite normally, it can be observed that their market entry has contributed to a reduction in the price of mobile telephone services."
However, pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are probably not part of the ÚOHS' interests.
In this case, the almost touching harmony of the three mobile operators resulting from their reactions is really shocking.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same petrol price at the petrol stations is certainly just coincidence and the result of a tough competition.
"The Authority has not discovered any signs of anti-competitive action in this matter and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way in the matter.
None of the suppliers has a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions on the market.
The regulatory authority for telecommunications is likely to lack the necessary tools to open up the mobile market to virtual providers," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, prepared by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
Of course, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the agreement of the network operator is always necessary for the market entry of a virtual provider.
And the mobile operator has - logically - the monopoly for his network.
This means that it necessarily occupies a dominant position in a particular segment.
Even if you do not follow this argument, it should at least be a warning to the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are strikingly similar.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including the mentioned company GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The transfer of responsibility to the ČTÚ is then a quite common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recent amendment to the Telecommunications Act has failed to enforce the extension of the ČTÚ's competences to the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know this all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's all right when no one's looking
First of all, the functioning of any pseudo-virtual provider, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
It is companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but are only partly public.
Usually they are companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others offer their own mobile telephone services.
The price lists of these companies are usually only available to selected ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classic company customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar kind of resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, it may be a violation of the contractual conditions that we will then deal with, which may lead to an end to the cooperation with the relevant company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing does not talk about the people responsible for mobile service providers.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned above, there may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such an approach.
In fact, from the activities of these companies, they receive not negligible profits, and at the same time, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such kinds of speculation, in spite of everything, the services of these companies are used only by a very small percentage of customers.
They also have to accept that the SIM card on their phone does not run on their name, so they cannot have it in full like the normal customers of mobile operators."
But the ČTÚ should at least seem strange.
A further question opens up for the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an approach, why are they blocking themselves from a virtual provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competence to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the declaration of the providers that they do not know anything about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit this.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been stressed several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers led to a significant drop in the price of the various services.
In virtually all countries where virtual providers have been created, the traditional providers have tried to prevent their emergence more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a market that was too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, at this very moment the regulatory bodies intervened, which did not seek to protect the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and this was followed by more.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing up the whole case like a hot potato.
On the basis of our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguity in competences is more than favourable in these cases.
But let's not throw the shotgun in the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile market may soon start moving again.
If a provider permits the emergence of a virtual mobile service provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting other interested parties (to discriminate).
And then the Czechs will finally make no more expensive calls than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Pick the best one
Listen to the four versions of the new Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new recordings of the national anthem "Where is my homeland" at a ceremony on the occasion of the Czech Statehood Day.
The hymn was newly recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - with male or female solo vocals, in choir version and in an instrumental version.
The vocal version was taken over by Kateřina Knková and Adam Plachetka.
The editors of the hymn versions are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to all four versions.
For Bělohlávek, the Czech national song is one of the most beautiful hymns.
He had already told Czech Radio that he had chosen singers with young, representative voices for the solo versions, which are distinctive and popular.
"From the very beginning, I tried to keep a clear diction on both and then with the choir, so that the text could be understood well, so that a harmony could be achieved," the conductor said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song "Kde domov můj" was first performed in 1834 on the stage of the stage theatre in the originally Czech play "Fidlovačka" by Josef Kajetán Tyl, the music was by František Škroup.
It became popular, and people spontaneously accepted it.
The first verse of the song became an organic part of the national anthem after the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
It remained one of the seven state symbols after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
How does the "new" hymn sound?
The Prague transport companies will also transport on a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1st, 2008 will enter the history of Prague's transport companies as a date when the first passengers who carry an electronic coupon in their pockets instead of a paper ticket will enter a subway, tram or bus.
These can currently buy about one hundred thousand people who own the chip card Opencard.
Passengers can buy a 30-day, 90-day or annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and can play it on their chip card at the same time, in the information centres and branches of the transport companies at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádra
The coupons are also available on the Internet since yesterday on the website of the transport companies www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by over four hundred customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who use Internet sales can really forget the output window in the subway stations, where they had to wait regularly in long queues for their paper tickets.
They buy the coupon via the Internet, which is played on the Opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"There is also a desk with trained staff available to travellers at these points, which advises interested parties on the Internet purchase and also places the coupon on the map," said Martin Opatrný, spokesman for the project.
In addition to the libraries, you can also play the electronic coupons on self-service machines on the opencard, which are installed in some underground vestibules.
What do such machines look like?
They are red, remind of ticket evaluation, the passengers may have already noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but it should be eighty by the end of the year," adds Opatrný.
The coupon is controlled by an automatic machine instead of the driver
The operation of the vending machines, which will work from tomorrow, is easy.
All you have to do is insert the chip card, and the previously purchased coupon plays itself.
The electronic coupons will apply from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburban trains and on the bus lines with numbers 300 to 499, with which especially the inhabitants from municipalities of the region of central Bohemia reach the capital.
"In the trains that are part of Prague's integrated traffic, the train attendants have reading devices that enable them to check the period of validity of the coupons according to time and zone," explains Filip Drápal of the Ropid organisation, who compiles the timetables for the Prague transport companies.
The suburban buses have card readers at the driver's ticket counter.
When boarding, the chip card must not only be presented to the driver, but the open card must be placed in a marked position on the side of the cash register.
Thus the driver checks the validity of the played coupons.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the coupons, nothing is easier than asking the driver for this information," says Drápal.
A passenger who does not drive suburban buses and no longer knows when the coupon expires can in turn go to the self-service machines where the coupons are played on the card.
Here the information about the validity of its documents is displayed on the display of the device.
