With such a wish, some groups of Sudeten Germans turned to the US President in 1945.
This can be seen, among other things, from a letter which has been preserved in a private archive and which is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian scientific library.
In the letter, the Germans of Krumau ask the American President not to allow the return of the "Sudetengaus" - which was taken by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Agreement - to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and really want to be sure of the words that the American units do not enter German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," says a letter signed with the words "people to whom the fate of the Sudeten lies at the heart."
Since the connection to Czechoslovakia makes the Sudeten Germans - knowing the Czech national character - suspect that they would expect brutality, ruthlessness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take over the protection over the Bohemian Forest for today and forever.
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the view of a quarter of a million inhabitants of this area, you are acknowledging a state that is foreign to us, which is trying to suppress and eliminate minorities and has done nothing at all to contribute to the victory of the Allies," the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is allegedly the fear of revenge by the "Czech oppressors".
If the US President has doubts about the attitude of the Bohemian Forest Germans, it is sufficient that he initiates a referendum in the Böhmerwaldgau on whether the inhabitants wanted to become part of the USA or live under the protective rule of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat naïve in today's knowledge of post-war history, some contemporary witnesses believe that it paints a good picture of the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at the time.
Even if the Czech Germans at least had to suspect that they would be negotiating their deportation from the Republic, only a few of them accepted such a possibility at all.
Some waited for the United States and Britain to negotiate some kind of autonomy for the Sudeten.
Still others believed that they could simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who comes from Budweis.
During the war he was employed as a German Budweiser in the Navy on the Baltic Sea.
When he was taken to a prisoner of war camp in Holstein at the end of the war, dozens of other Bohemian Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that if they came home, the Czech would suit them," said Chalupa.
In his opinion, none of the German prisoners of war who had lived in Czechoslovakia before the war expected that he would be expelled from the Republic on the basis of the Beneš decrees.
