Among scientists, a mysterious phenomenon has been causing confusion for years - the swing-by-anomal.
The swing-by is a flight manoeuvre of space probes, in which they receive additional momentum in the gravitational field of a celestial body, such as the Earth.
This allows the probes to save a lot of fuel.
The European-American research probe Cassini-Huygens used this physical trick as well as the solar probe Ulysses.
What the researchers have been wondering about for years, however, is that the missiles do not behave 100 percent as would be expected under the time-honoured law of gravity.
On the contrary, irregularities occur at the rate of speed.
The probes become unexpectedly faster or slower.
So far, the physicists have not been able to explain this effect.
They baptized him Swing-by-Anomaly.
Some experts fear that even Albert Einstein's general theory of relativity, which describes the attraction of matter through a curvature of space, might not be entirely correct.
American physicist Stephen Adler from Princeton's Institute for Advanced Study still firmly believes that Einstein was not wrong, and tries to explain the swing-by anomaly using the so-called dark matter that astronomers have identified in the universe.
"Responsible for the anomaly could be dark matter, which could also be very close to the Earth," he writes.
Space researchers have only known about the existence of dark matter for about ten years.
It is obviously an attraction whose effect on other celestial bodies can be observed.
On the other hand, it itself is completely invisible, i.e. it does not transmit and reflect any electromagnetic radiation, especially no visible light.
According to scientists’ calculations, dark matter accounts for just over a fifth of the total mass of the universe.
