Debate on bilingual education: Education in English-speaking environments
In this issue of the Education Watch, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of candidates for bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, Senior Researcher in California Studies and Senior Director in the Department of Education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book "Not as good as you think: Why the middle class needs a school selection".
Addressing the Hispanic voters is a complicated task.
Barrack Obama's proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama's election campaign mentions that "the probability of Afro-American and Hispanic students successfully completing school is lower than that of white students" - which is true.
To close this gap, Obama’s educational plan specifically recommends, among other things, a bilingual transition period in education for those who are learning English.
Nevertheless, the question for Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which focuses on teaching in languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the gap in school performance.
Take Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have only recently arrived in the country, learn English.
Nevertheless, in 2008 an astonishing 100 percent of fourth grade students passed the state examination in math at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of the children from the fourth school year were rated as good in the English exam.
This amazing success was achieved with other methods than those preferred by Obama.
The school Sixth Street places its emphasis on review and exercise, on constant control of knowledge and an attitude that does not tolerate exceptions.
