Conversation - From blood that became safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to be happy because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
Above all, it has regained public confidence, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
It is known that during the 1980s national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross blood donation service were contaminated with the HIV virus and hepatitis C virus.
In the face of this drama and public discontent, in February 1994 the Government of Canada launched a public inquiry led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to draw up guidelines to prevent another disaster of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to submit his report, several provinces set up a committee to develop a new system for the administration of canned blood in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mandate.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, who is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
`1998, when Hema-Quebec started her work, hardly 38% of people had confidence in the blood canning system in Quebec, remembers Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood preserves and through the work in this field during the following years, we have regained public confidence', she says, before proudly stressing that in early 2008 nearly 94% of Quebec's population now had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that 'trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has been acting on the principle of caution.
At that time, we witnessed the emergence of numerous cases of the human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, this woman, who has been in charge since her founding in 1998.
'And we didn't have the slightest idea if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we relied on one of the main guidelines of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which exclusion measures are applied if you do not know this and if a disease progresses only slowly, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which manifests itself through a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, there was no doubt that this disease was transmitted through the blood.
So this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied has quite a purpose.
In 1999, a much more precise technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which enable the virus to be detected directly in the donor's blood, and not the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST enabled the incubation time to be reduced between the time the person was infected and when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than one week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors might be infected without knowing it, and one could not see it, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are in danger of getting HIV - infected blood.
"In other words, you have to distribute 12 million blood cans before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 cans of blood each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted via a blood preserve occurs.
I believe that you can feel comfortable these days when you get or prescribe a blood transfusion to restore your health,' says the director of Hema-Quebec.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can get into the system.
Only last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted through the blood by insects.
We need to monitor continuously,' continues Dr. Décary, before stressing that Hema-Quebec must provide adequate supplies in addition to a secure supply.
`The need is increasing because the population is aging.
As anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor network, which includes on average only 3% of Quebec's residents suitable for blood donation.'
Every healthy person, who is 18 years of age or older and meets the eligibility criteria, can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who make their blood available are not accepted because, for example, they suffer from AIDS or malaria, and those who have travelled to a country where malaria is spread are excluded from blood donation for one year.
`With these 3%, we manage to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Poor supplies are very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It's hard to convince people to donate blood, but especially to keep them and get them to become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that you rarely find the time to spend an hour donating blood,' regrets Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood preserves, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is almost exclusively used for severe fire injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages Quebec's only public umbilical cord blood bank.
The umbilical cord, formerly considered a biomedical waste, contains blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
A few weeks ago we celebrated the storage of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to remove more than a thousand annually.
'We should probably start making it available for transplants at the beginning of next year,' explains Dr. Décary, who describes this program of umbilical cord blood loss as very popular.
'Many mothers are convinced that they have no access to it', because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
