'Everything was done to protect the real economy and the American people from the price crisis on Wall Street,' declared the Democrat.
'This is the basic point: if we don't do this, the trauma, chaos and unrest in the daily life of the Americans will be enormous,' explained Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had accelerated over the last two hours, for fear of the effect that a renewed failure would have had on the mood of investors.
The deadline that had been agreed was the market opening this morning.
The two American presidential candidates, who took part in the negotiations only late, were more likely to be supporters of the agreement, but without failing to express their dissatisfaction with the need to meet them in this extreme way.
Democratic Senator Barrack Obama insisted on adding certain resolutions to the agreement, especially those designed to allow the owners to keep their homes, and those concerning the salaries of the executives of the state-saved companies.
"When you ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of certain people, that is nothing to congratulate.
