The psychology of overbidding - or why we are willing to pay more
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the bid.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in "Science" magazine, people do not want to be beaten in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers should play Lotto while the other took part in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the subjects were examined by functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the cerebral cortex, was measured in losers of the auction, in which the overbidding of the opponent plays an essential role.
Among many other functions, this region of the brain is responsible for the "self-remuneration" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to support their thesis, economists in the research group have additionally carried out investigations to track the money.
In this case, three groups should bid against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their bets.
Another group were also promised $15 reward in case they emerge as winners from the game.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in the event of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was therefore only that the emphasis was on winning, while the other was on losing.
However, as proof of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the "against losing" group were willing to make higher bets than those in the control or "win" group.
"These results cannot be derived from previous economic theory.
These have so far only justified the behaviour observed at auctions with the pleasure of winning or risk avoidance.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so we now have a third explanation" - said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should the doctor be consulted?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death in Hungary.
The number of people infected in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, due to the fact that patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the generic term for infectious liver disease caused by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and the diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (e.g. sperm, vaginal secretion or saliva).
In any case, travellers are recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B, and there is no vaccine against virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A are approximately two-three weeks after consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes light, the urine dark, and recovery can take up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, around 1 million people die every year from hepatitis B-induced diseases, which are far more severe, such as liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten people infected is in drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen destroys the liver cells insidiously - in many cases the first symptoms show up after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the family doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
Recognised in good time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thereby eliminating the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30th is the World Day of Hepatitis, held for the first time in 2004 by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to increase awareness of this chronic liver infection caused by viruses, their development and the importance of early detection.
Do believers have less pain?
As the latest research shows, religious faith acts like a kind of "painful remedy" that is said to have facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have carried out an interesting experiment: It was investigated to what extent belief in God influences the feeling of pain of man, reports the British newspaper "Telegraph".
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists each received electric shocks while studying a painting by the Mother of God.
The results showed that the faithful were able to eliminate most of the pain.
By means of a brain scan technology, it could even be proven that Catholics could activate the part of their brain responsible for pain regulation.
The study was the first in a research project involving scientists, philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university.
During the experiment, a sparkling device was attached to the left hand, which gave off the electric shocks.
Participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: on the one hand a painting of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other hand Leonardo da Vinci's "Dame with the Hermelin".
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary among the faithful would create a kind of religious trance, while they chose da Vinci's image, because it was hardly different from the other painting and felt as comforting.
The subjects each spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, receiving a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages while viewing either the religious or the other painting.
Catholics reported that at the sight of the Mother of God they felt "safe" as if they were "concerned" and they felt "peace and peace".
While viewing the religious painting, they reported 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo's work in mind.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also took part in the experiment, said that one could also produce similar effects with other, strong-looking images with the atheists, one only had to find the corresponding photo.
"We would have to find an image that triggers very positive sensations, such as a mother or a father," the psychologist says.
The Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"Practising the faith should change our personality, and it does so in many cases," Wright says.
After these excellent results, only the question remains, what effect a Madonna image of Leonardo or another comparable painter would have on the pain regulation of the faithful.
Would the high-quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
You are what you share about yourself
On the occasion of her tenth birthday, Google can rightly claim that she can be found in people's pockets just as she can be found above their heads in the sky: she knows where people have spent their holidays, what specialists they go to, and what moves her.
