In an interview with the Financial Times recently, Schmidt said that Google's main goal was to collect even more personal data about the users and thus to get closer to the original goal of the company, according to which it wanted to "order all the information of this world".
Schmidt explained that after ten years of world-changing work, Google is still at the beginning of collecting information.
Asked about the status quo in five years, Schmidt said: he wanted Google to be able to answer questions like "What should I do tomorrow?" or "What job really suits me?", but software programs are not yet able to do so, as they do not know enough about the users.
Not all Internet users are aware that in the course of their Internet searches the search terms would be registered, as well as the IP addresses from which they were searched and the pages visited.
For example, the "Personalized Search" introduced two years ago allows visitors to save their own search history and to use it later so that the results can be generated much more precisely later, and the so-called "recommendations" are also based on the same logic with which the system recommends tailor-made products and services based on previous preferences.
However, the users wonder what happens in the event of data misuse - "When you look at what I do" - some people are worried about the Google data monopoly.
In most cases, however, it is more the company's representation of potential power that is frightening, and less the sense of guilt or fear of punishment, the pursuit of freedom, or the revolt against power that many Internet users are opposed to.
However, it is a proven fact that the search terms are not only stored, but also passed on to third parties in the event of an occasion, and in these cases there is no protection for the personal rights of the Internet user.
A prime example of this was the recent action against paedophilia in Brazil, during which Google provided the Brazilian government with information collected by the community site called "Orkut" and also made it possible to identify the paedophilia.
However, users concerned about personal rights were able to breathe a sigh of relief in May when Google, together with the civil rights organization EFF, successfully appealed against the FBI in court: therefore, Google cannot be forced to release information to the FBI on secret request with any point of the Constitution in the future.
(However, the Federal Government has successfully obtained the publication of 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms with reference to the Youth Protection Act adopted years ago, but has been retroactively withheld from it the list of individual users, or their web and search terms list, for two months.)
So Google's image remains controversial: those who are reluctant to release their personal data because they fear the loss of their privacy and privacy through the use of Google services, scourge the company with the outrage due to conservative companies.
However, the American "geek culture", which is present in many countries and unites enthusiastic computer fans, activists and users, sees the next generation of "cool entrepreneurs" in them, unlike Microsoft, which is market leader thanks to Windows, even if both are fighting for the same goal.
One possible reason for this is that, unlike Microsoft, Google does not require identification codes for its users and provides its services free of charge, so that an open, constantly updated source code and program package seems to be far more attractive, youthful and cool than the official practices of the software giant.
On the other hand, the geeks see through the problematic relationship of personal rights and the Internet razor-sharp - a relationship that has come to the fore especially in recent years thanks to the term "Web 2.0".
The "Web 2.0" is about nothing but collaboration, i.e. the users deliberately leave traces and use the available communication channels, and even if the dimensions are individually different, the main thing remains the same, namely to show itself publicly.
An average youth can simultaneously manage his profile on several community portals - from Facebook via Xanga, it can connect through other services, such as Twitter, or music services such as last.fm, and can eventually integrate all of this into a tracking system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. In addition, they can run blogs that automatically display the latest photo galleries that are geosted on Flickr or Picasa.
And a number of other exemplary cases prove: When looking at the party photos last night, the girlfriend soon finds out who her unfaithful friend has been enjoying himself with, or the employee is dismissed because in his blog he is only too honest about his anger about the management of the company - one thing is for sure: the term "privacy" has now been completely reinterpreted.
Those who lead an online life are what they reveal themselves to be - in a way, one could formulate the basic idea behind the behavior of today's youth.
And if you try to keep something secret, or even bypass Google's monopoly, you can do so - such as with Scroogle, a tool that, although accessing Google's search engine, deliberately leaves no traces.
Quite a few people deliberately don't register on community sites so they can't be found, but Google's online applications, such as text processing and graphical tools and RSS feeds, can also deal with alternative versions that are not linked to huge server parks and therefore don't generate the best possible profile from the user.
Public opinion, however, is anxiously waiting for Google to show its true face.
With its current value of USD 156 billion, the company is even ahead of IBM (USD 140 billion), Intel (USD 124 billion) or Coca-Cola (USD 110 billion), AdWords/AdSense's advertising space is threatening the revenue of advertising agencies, and the increasingly rapid introduction of services is causing worry not only to Microsoft but also to other software developers.
However, critical observers also find the disturbing counter-poles: for example, the corporate management has completely rejected a protest by the employees after the company's own kindergarten fees have doubled, and management also said that the staff's multiple meals are too expensive. However, all this seems to be mildly opposed to Google even falling to the knees in 2006 in front of the Chinese government and agreeing to an agreement that all hits critical of the regime, or those that violate the good taste, would be filtered out.
The internal regulation of the Group states that no new service will be advertised in advance, but only when it is already available. Nevertheless, the events of the coming months and years could again change strongly: While some believe that Google's book and magazine scan or archiving project is now assuming dimensions that the company would soon have to deal with the Supreme Court, others are rather concerned about the health system, which allows the creation of a complete health profile based on findings, doctors and problems.
And the fact that Google is building up a genetic database already provides the next generation of sci-fi authors with the material - such as "Scroogled", the famous novel by Cory Doctorow describes in best Orwellian manner a future in which a person becomes frighteningly approachable thanks to data obtained from Google.
