Járóka: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today, in Paris, the European Summit on Equal Opportunities has begun, which is being hosted by the Presidency of the European Union, France.
In her speech addressed to the plenary session, Lívia Járóka, Fidesz MEP of the European People's Party, drew attention in particular to the educational segregation, which is one of the most serious violations of the rights of Roma children, and was also the main obstacle to their need for validity.
The high-level conference was opened by the French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs, Xavier Bertrand, on behalf of the French Presidency, and Vladimir Spidla, EU Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Among the participants were representatives of governments, the European social partners, as well as the most important European legal protection and citizens' organisations in the field of equal opportunities.
According to Fidesz' press office, Járóka pointed out that, in addition to discrimination in the search for a job, the Roma were primarily displaced from the labour market because of their low level of education.
"The vast majority of Roma young people do not have middle school education, and due to poor primary education, only a small part of them can obtain a university degree."
Furthermore, Járóka stressed that education is a fundamental human right, which would play a key role in asserting other human rights.
Investing in the early education of Roma children could strengthen the economy of the EU member states.
In the view of the House, it is important that a broad circle - Roma and non-Roma - should be aware of these links.
The earlier a Roma student starts school, the more his or her chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market increase; and through income and turnover tax they contribute to national spending.
"As EU citizens, the Roma must be guaranteed the right to high-quality education - the poor and segregated education must be stopped", said Lívia Járóka.
As the honourable Member said, a common, target- and action-oriented approach by the European Union is necessary to speed up the disengagement process in the education sector, which requires proper compliance with existing and planned anti-discrimination directives.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation, and unemployment, and give Roma children the democratic means to contribute to the future of Europe as a fully entitled citizen," Járóka said.
Since last year's congress in Berlin, the summit has been held annually with the aim of creating a unique forum for the advancement of the objectives of equal opportunities and freedom of discrimination at European, but also national, level, in the sense of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities".
