Napolitano: "Prevention of accidents at work is crucial"
Every day, 2500 accidents at work occur in Italy, three people die and 27 remain inactive for life.
For 2007, data from the Inail (Istituto nazionale contro gli infortuni sul Lavoro) confirm that the fatal accidents at work were about 1200.
These figures prove the seriousness of a phenomenon that causes almost twice as many deaths as murders.
Today, the Anmil (Associazione Nazionale Mutilati e Invalidi del Lavoro) will celebrate the 58th national day for the victims of accidents at work in all the provinces of Italy, in order to draw the attention of social institutions and the media to this dramatic situation.
"The worrying data disseminated by Anmil and the tragic news of these days confirm how crucial the issue of prevention in the workplace is," confirms the President of the Republic of Giorgio Napolitano in his communication to the President of the Amil (Associazione nazionale mutilati ed invalidi del lavoro) Pietro Mercandelli.
The head of state expresses his "great appreciation for the constant commitment to prevention in the workplace, to the protection of injured workers, to aid the families of the victims and to raise public opinion".
"An outraged "basta" has risen to this; understandable in tragedies, which, measured by their magnitude, trigger some vortex in the media and public participation. However, everyday reality often confronts us with dramatic events, which can even repeat themselves in their own dynamics."
Napolitano does not hide that "there is definitely also a resource problem: it must be invested decisively in education and information."
The numerous initiatives for a more direct awareness of the school framework by young people who are nourishing the world of work are particularly important.
It is our duty to focus attention on this phenomenon and not to divert attention from its social seriousness. It is necessary to put into effect and improve a legislative norm.
For his part, the President of the Chamber, Gianfranco Fini, stressed "how the phenomenon of work-related deaths constitutes an urgent social emergency that offends the conscience of all of us and forces all institutions to work towards decisive rules that aim to put an end to the problem".
"Data on accidents at work seem to indicate a slight improvement, but this does not rule out the fact that the number of work-related deaths is far too high," stresses Anmil President Pietro Mercandelli.
"We don't want this "positive tendency" to mean less attention, which is exactly what causes the tragedy in the end."
"We believe that you are doing too little to counter the phenomenon of accidents. You can fight against it through various actions.
We believe that stronger controls and inspections are necessary – according to Mercandelli; but also stronger measures to educate the workers who are already starting at school."
"Another effort is necessary - he adds - in terms of communication and awareness of public opinion.
But above all, a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers towards a phenomenon that constitutes a social emergency is in demand."
Mercandelli also referred to "the progressive deterioration of protection for the victims of industrial accidents" and denounced the "abolition of the social system against which we are fighting in recent years".
"The aim is therefore to return a guarantee to the employee on insurance, so that the fate of the victim of an industrial accident does not depend on voluntary or random donations, which are currently decided by a legislator."
Mp3 player under charge: danger of hearing damage
Listening to loud music over a longer period of time with portable music devices, such as Mp3 players, can lead to permanent hearing damage.
This is reported by the European Commission, which cites the opinion of the EU's Csrseri (scientific committee on current and recently identified health risks) in a report published today in Brussels.
"The report states that 5-10% of those who listen to loud music with portable music equipment for at least five years a week for more than one hour a day risk permanent loss of hearing," says one comment.
"I am worried that such a large number of young people, who usually place portable music devices and mobile phones at a high volume, will irretrievably damage their hearing without knowing it," says Meglena Kuneva.
"From the scientific findings – as it is said on the part of the European Union – there is a clear risk that pushes too fast action.
What really matters is to raise consumer awareness and make this information a common good.
In the light of these scientific findings, we must review the existing control systems so that they are fully effective and keep up with the new technology".
Brussels had commissioned the independent scientific committee in view of the widespread use of portable music equipment among young people.
"Scientists - the EU communication concludes - confirm that there is a legitimate concern and that the European Commission, together with the other EU members and stakeholders, will now investigate the necessary measures to better protect children and young people from the noise coming from portable music equipment and similar equipment ".
There is already a European standard which limits the level of noise from portable music equipment to 100 dB, and concerns about the damage that could result from too much noise pollution.
This damage can be very limited by resorting to solutions such as reducing the volume and length of the noise exposure.
In its report, the Scientific Committee of the Eu points out that when users of portable music devices hear loud (more than 89 decibels) music only five hours a week, so that the legal limits that apply to the maximum noise level at the workplace are already exceeded.
Those who exceed this limit risk the complete loss of hearing within five years.
This is 5-10 % of users of such devices, the number of which can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
