The elite is in danger
The phenomenon had already emerged a few days ago when the Chamber of Deputies voted against the White House's 700 billion savings package: a large part of Americans were and is more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday's issue of the New York Times, which tells of how the crisis in progress divides the Republican party, which is increasingly splitting into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which has always favored state institutions and business community, and those neoconservatives that are hostile to "those in Washington" and to the financial world and, above all, win voters in the south and the centre of states.
This part of the party owes its rise to the voice of the one I mentioned above.
However, this example, just mentioned, is only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake heralds or even already represents: not only in the US, but also throughout the West and perhaps beyond it, will they be affected.
Both in the states and in Europe, the crisis seems to speed up the long-afraid events that are finally taking shape and coming to light under these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the new discovery, the unprecedented renaissance of the state in connection with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
In fact, the crisis is a decline of the banking and financial institutions, which have close links with foreign countries and at the same time manage an enormous amount of the assets of private households living in a single state.
This is an immediate political problem for governments: how to deal with the families concerned, which are also an enormous mass of voters.
The crisis thus appears economically global, whereas politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism seems to have fallen into disrepute and lost its right to speak: the clear proof of this has been given by the EU, which, due to its division into different national and international conflicts, cannot find a common path.
Therefore, everyone now expects the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and above all distribution of aid funds: Since the crisis became ever more serious, only the US is in the economic situation to save itself without foreign help.
And in addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus, two conditions that cannot be overvalued – under certain circumstances – which no international organisation or market will otherwise be able to rely on in a similar way.
The new emphasis placed on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever greater importance which has recently been associated in the economy with a closely related sector: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is just now that we were so convinced that we had long since entered a networked empire, a realm of ever-differentiated technologies, of the immaterial, that we must suddenly discover how our future will depend more and more on essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
These can certainly all be transported from one place to the other of the world, but they are still extremely connected to a closely defined piece of earth – a territory.
Therefore, the one who has such a territory is in favor of another who lives in an area without harvest, without water or without oil.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, requires a short insertion.
Who territory, who government, who says politics, thus also says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to generate two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leaderships, that is, the need for someone who knows how to regulate things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation over the existing leaderships, especially those of the economy that have turned out to be inadequate and full of shadow zones.
In addition, there is a deeper and, in a sense, even more disturbing aspect: a loss of confidence, an intolerance, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, all of which is directed at a whole class of Western managers.
The conviction among large sections of the population seems to be paving the way for the fact that it is not only the actions of the social elite, but already their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose content is more and more alien and traditional to the majority.
The demand for leadership is thus fueling a branched but powerful movement of the disempowerment of the leading class and the traditional political establishment. This manifests itself in unforeseen "revolts" of the voters and in the sudden reversal of the collective state of mind of recent times: starting with the rise of the conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, about the collapse of the Labour Party in Great Britain, towards the rebellion of the American deputies against Bush (and perhaps also the victory of the right in Italy plays a role here).
One gets the impression that the old elite, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, magazines, intellectual creditors, some would say their format, more and more problems of understanding and therefore less representative value regarding what is going on in the lower social classes of the West today and is being intensified by the financial crisis and driven to over-dimensionality.
In view of all this, it would be simply exaggerated to speak of a "rebelion of the masses".
But keeping your eyes wide is certainly not.
