Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Be careful of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed in summer due to their refreshing quality and vitamin richness, can cause serious health damage if they are taken at the same time as certain vital medicines, since they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
David Bailey, professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly points to the risk of packaging as well as fresh fruit juices associated with drug intake. During the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he again sounded the alarm: a glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice is sufficient to reduce the absorption capacity of certain vital medicines to the extent that they are virtually eliminated and thus endanger the health of patients.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected to be responsible for increasing the effects of some medicines such as antibiotics, antiasthmatics, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytic and neurological agents, up to toxic levels.
MEDICALS IN DRIVER – In a report two years ago, the same agency had warned doctors and patients about the dangers of this mix and stressed the need to take care of what is being drunk in conjunction with drugs such as diazepan or metadon.
IT IS NOT ONLY GRAPEFRUIT – According to the experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the medicines.
The list of active substances inhibited by fruit juices is long.
Therefore the appeal of Michele Carruba, director of the Università Statale di Milano: "Such results are usually forwarded immediately to the various international manufacturers, who are thus free to change the consumer information.
It is therefore advisable to always read the package leaflet and, if there is still some uncertainty, to ask a pharmacist or doctor", the expert of the Ansa Agency stresses.
