On request, you can have the installation CD sent to your home or office.
However, if cost-freeness can be an incentive for the dissemination of the programme in private households, it is also particularly in the area of business where OpenOffice could succeed in the big leap: after all, various public administration and school institutions have already moved to OpenOffice.
In fact, there is not even a lack of training, which means optimal help for small and medium-sized enterprises, and thus even opens up business prospects.
OpenOffice consists of five main components: Writer, the Word corresponding text creation program; Calc, the table program which aims at a displacement of Excel; Impress, to create presentations like with PowerPoint; Dbase to operate databases instead of the more known access; and lastly Draw, a graphics module.
The objective for 2008 is to achieve 5 million downloads – a goal that can be easily exceeded with already reached 3 million and 600 thousand.
